{{For|the Ukrainian football (soccer) player|Oleksandr Zinchenko (footballer)}}
{{for|the Ukrainian developmental psychologist|Pyotr Zinchenko}}
[[File:Zinchenko oleksandr december05.jpg|thumb|Oleksandr Zinchenko in December 2005]]
'''Oleksandr Oleksiovich Zinchenko''' ({{lang-ua|Олександр Олексійович Зінченко}}; April 16, 1957 in [[Slavuta]] – June 9, 2010 in [[Kiev]]<ref name=Feofaniya/>) was a [[Ukraine|Ukrainian]] politician who was Director-General of the [[National Space Agency of Ukraine]] from 2009 to 2010. Oleksandr Zinchenko had a controversial career that includes [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[Komsomol]] leadership, business in [[Russia]] and Ukraine, participation in the pro-[[Leonid Kuchma]] [[Social Democratic Party of Ukraine (united)]], survival of [[cancer]] and joining the anti-Kuchma opposition.<ref name=Siddiqui>[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/69286/ Oleksandr Zinchenko dies at age 53], [[Kyiv Post]] (June 10, 2010)</ref>

Zinchenko was an Academician of the National TV Academy of Ukraine and has received the Honored Journalist of Ukraine award. He was married to a TV host, Iryna, and had two daughters, Kateryna and Oleksandra.<ref name=June9/>

==Biography==
Zinchenko was born in [[Slavuta]] ([[Khmelnytskyi Oblast]], then [[Ukrainian SSR]]) on April 16, 1957. He graduated with a degree in physics from [[Chernivtsi University]], where from 1983-1985 he headed the Komsomol youth organization. From 1993-1995 Zinchenko headed Ometa-Merkantail and the joint stock company Balchug in Kiev . In 1996 he was appointed director of the Ukraine-Express information agency and worked as president of [[Inter TV]] in 1996 he also joined the [[Social Democratic Party of Ukraine (united)]] (SDPU(o)).<ref name=June9/>

Zinchenko became the SDPU(o)’s chief deputy chairman (vice-Speaker) of the [[Verkhovna Rada]] (parliament) in 1998 and headed the party’s parliament faction. In 2000, he chaired the parliament’s Freedom of Speech and Information Committee, which international media watchdogs criticized for doing little to bolster the freedom of speech in Ukraine. One of the tapes (dated May 2000) recorded by Kuchma's former bodyguard, Major [[Mykola Melnychenko]] in [[President of Ukraine|President]] [[Kuchma]] office (revealed during the [[Cassette Scandal]]) Zinchenko seemed to talk with Kuchma about efforts to co-opt critical journalists and harass media outlets.<ref>[http://www.kyivpost.com/nation/22247 Know your leaders!], [[Kyiv Post]] (27 January 2005)</ref> Zinchenko was [[Ukrainian parliamentary election, 2002|re-elected to the Verkhovna Rada in 2002]] on a SDPU(o) ticket.<ref name=apa>[http://www.kyivpost.com/nation/21265 SDPU(u)'s Zinchenko joins Our Ukraine], [[Kyiv Post]] (16 June 2004)</ref>

In June 2004<ref name=apa/> Zinchenko was appointed Campaign manager for [[Viktor Yushchenko]] during the [[Ukrainian presidential election, 2004]]<ref>[http://www.kyivpost.com/world/21766 Moroz will back Yushchenko], [[Kyiv Post]] (5 November 2004)</ref> and after Yushchenko victory served as a [[Presidential Administration of Ukraine|chief of the President's office]] for Yuschenko in 2005. In September 2005 he resigned from the latter position in protest against [[Political corruption|corruption]] he alleged was taking place in the inner circle of the President, mainly accusing [[Petro Poroshenko]].<ref>[http://www.kyivpost.com/opinion/editorial/23161 Zinchenko's bombshell], [[Kyiv Post]] (7 September 2005)</ref> In December 2005 he created the political party ''Oleksander Zinchenko’s Patriotic Forces Party of Ukraine''.<ref>[http://www.kyivpost.com/nation/23653 Oleksandr Zinchenko talks], [[Kyiv Post]] (21 December 2005)</ref>

Zinchenko is member of the [[Kiev City Council]] for [[Bloc Yulia Tymoshenko]]<ref>[http://photo.unian.net/eng/themes/10356 Events by themes: «Yuliya Timoshenko’s bloc» faction deputies press-conference in UNIAN about the system tariffs increase in Kiev, [[UNIAN]] photoservice, (26-11-2008)]</ref><ref>[http://www.kmr.gov.ua/delegates.asp?Id=640 Kiev City Council Official web-site – Delegates section] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090203172044/http://kmr.gov.ua/delegates.asp?Id=640 |date=2009-02-03 }}</ref> from the [[Kiev local election, 2008]] till his resignation in June 2009 he was the faction leader.<ref>[http://www.kyivpost.com/city/43872 Bloc of Yulia Tymoshenko in Kyiv City Council replaces Zinchenko with Melikhova], [[Kyiv Post]] (June 23, 2009)</ref>

On February 13, 2009 he was appointed Director General of the [[National Space Agency of Ukraine]],<ref>[http://www.nkau.gov.ua/nsau/newsnsau.nsf/mainsubjectsE/B6608C815C948526C225755C005D72E0?openDocument&Lang=E Olexander Zinchenko is appointed Director General of the National Space Agency of Ukraine], [[National Space Agency of Ukraine]] Official web-site (13 February 2009)</ref><ref>[http://www.interfax.com.ua/eng/main/8614/ Zinchenko's appointment as director general of NSAU is 'a mockery of the rocket and space industry,' says Ukraine's ex-president], [[Interfax|Interfax-Ukraine]] (February 20, 2009)</ref> he was relieved of this post in March 2010.<ref name=June9/>

Oleksandr Zinchenko died on June 9, 2010 at the age of 53,<ref name=June9>[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/69164/ Oleksandr Zinchenko, politician who turned away from Kuchma to support Orange Revolution, dies], [[Kyiv Post]] (June 9, 2010)</ref> and was buried at Kiev's [[Baikove Cemetery]] on June 11.<ref name=Feofaniya>[http://www.kyivpost.com/news/politics/detail/69198/ Zinchenko to be buried at Baikove cemetery on June 11], [[Kyiv Post]] (June 10, 2010)</ref> [[Politics of Ukraine|Ukrainian politicians]] [[Yulia Tymoshenko]], [[Oleksandr Turchynov]], [[Mykola Tomenko]] and [[Borys Tarasyuk]] were present at his funeral.<ref>{{uk icon}} [http://www.byut.com.ua/photo/list/241.html# Юлія Тимошенко попрощалась з Олександром Зінченком, 11/06/2010], [[Bloc Yulia Tymoshenko]] official website (June 11, 2010)</ref>

